				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>As you probably know by now, ScottsBassLessons is <em>not just</em> about licks, grooves and chops… What I'm striving to do here is to give you a 'non-reductive' approach to learning and playing the bass.</p>
<p>That said, I'm not '<a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/licks/video-bass-lesson-ii-v-i-jazz-lick-1.html">anti-lick</a>' at all! What I'm saying is that it's not <em>enough</em> to learn a ton of bass licks, particularly if you want to be able to play with other musicians. But learning bass licks and grooves is a part of your musical education and you'll benefit even more from learning if you understand how they are constructed, so you can create your owns.</p>
<p>So today I'm going to show you a simple jazz lick for <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/licks/jazz-lick-major-7th-type-chords-1.html">Major 7th</a> type chords. It's built mainly over the C major arpeggio --btw. have you watched my lesson <a title="Practice Arpeggios on the Bass" href="http://scottsbasslessons.com/technique/practice-bass-arpeggios.html">practicing arpeggios on the bass</a>? When I say it's simple, I mean the way it's constructed is very simple, but make sure you use appropriate fingerings, by copying mine, for example. ;)</p>
<p><div><a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/bass-academy" class="post_cta">Full tab/notation & workbook available to Academy members &raquo;</a></div><div class="video_wrap "><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/pO3gZP4s2QE" width="560" height="349" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></div></p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/licks/jazz-lick-major-7th-type-chords-1.html">Jazz Lick for Major 7th Type Chords #1 (L#25)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com">Online Bass Lessons</a>.</p>
